headlines.headline: Why women are burning themselves in Iraqi Kurdistan

features.summary: In the Kurdistan region, women who feel trapped in abusive households often see suicide by self-immolation as their only way out.

media.title: 'I wish I hadn't survived': Why women burn themselves in Iraqi Kurdistan

synopses.short: 'I wish I hadn't survived': Why women burn themselves in Iraqi Kurdistan
synopses.long: Women in Iraq have been facing rising levels of domestic abuse. Cases of gender-based violence have seen a surge of 125% between 2020 and 2021, according to the UN. In the Kurdistan region, women who feel trapped in abusive households, often see suicide by self-immolation as their only way out. The Kurdistan Regional Government has tried to combat violence against women, but many remain at risk. The BBC has been granted rare access to one of the main hospitals for burns in Iraqi Kurdistan, where many women die of self-inflicted burns.
